application scenario

JavaGSEADIY

clusterProfilerGSEADIYFigureYa60GSEA_clusterprofiler

Using the output of the Java version of GSEA as input, do-it-yourself result map, drawing multiple pathways into a single map.

If you do GSEA analysis with clusterProfiler and want to DIY the result plots, plot multiple pathways to a single plot, or plot multiple comparisons of the same pathway to a single plot, use FigureYa60GSEA_clusterprofiler.

JavaGSEAExcelExcel

xls

Output folder of GSEA for Java has an Excel file for each pathway, copy the Excel file for the pathway you are interested in to the current folder.

Read xls file and merge

fnames <- Sys.glob("*.xls")
fdataset <- lapply(fnames,read.delim)
names(fdataset) <- fnames
result <- ldply(fdataset, data.frame)
result$pathway <- unlist(strsplit(result$.id,split = ".xls"))

Start drawing

GSEAExcelJavaGSEAGSEAExcelenrichment scoreenrichment score

Redrawing the image with the official GSEA output Excel file is best for drawing this kind of scatterplot. If you draw a line graph, you will find that it is not consistent with the image output from the Java version of GSEA. Thats because the official GSEA output Excel file is not the enrichment score for all genes, it only gives the enrichment score for genes within this pathway.

enrichment score + rank

Figure 1: Dot Plot (enrichment score) + Barcode (rank)

First, draw a dot plot.

ppoint <- ggplot(result, aes(x=RANK.IN.GENE.LIST,
                             y=RUNNING.ES,fill=pathway,group=pathway))+
  #
  #the advantage of using dots with black circles is that you can see that there are multiple dots in locations where the dots are dense
  geom_point(shape=21) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = mycol) + # draw dots with custom colors
  labs(x = "", y = "Enrichment Score", title = "") + 
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) + #xy0 let both the x and y axes start at 0
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0),
                     limits =c(min(result$RUNNING.ES-0.02), max(result$RUNNING.ES+0.02))) + 
  theme_classic() + 
  theme(axis.line.x = element_blank(),axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),axis.text.x = element_blank()) + #x remove x-axis
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) #0x draw the x-axis at position 0
ppoint

Redraw barcode

The scatterplot and the barcode plot behind it already show the gene rank by itself, in fact, only the line plot needs to draw the gene rank separately.

prank <- ggplot(result,aes(RANK.IN.GENE.LIST,pathway,colour=pathway))+
  geom_tile()+
  theme_bw() + # remove background color
  scale_color_manual(values = mycol) + # draw dots with custom colors
  labs(x = "treatment<--------------control", y = "", title = "") + 
  scale_x_discrete(expand = c(0, 0)) + scale_y_discrete(expand = c(0, 0)) +#xy0 let both the x and y axes start at 0
  theme(panel.grid =element_blank()) + # remove gridlines
  theme(panel.border = element_blank()) + # remove outer border
  theme(axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"))+
  theme(axis.line.y = element_blank(),axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),axis.text.y = element_blank())+ #y remove y-axis
  guides(color=FALSE)#color hide the legend generated by color
## Warning: The `<scale>` argument of `guides()` cannot be `FALSE`. Use "none" instead as
## of ggplot2 3.3.4.

Composite image

#gridExtra
#use gridExtra to keep the heights of the top and bottom graphs separate
gA=ggplot_gtable(ggplot_build(ppoint)) #ppoint2 or ppoint2
gB=ggplot_gtable(ggplot_build(prank))
maxWidth = grid::unit.pmax(gA$widths, gB$widths)
gA$widths <- as.list(maxWidth)
gB$widths <- as.list(maxWidth)

#gridx
#then combine the two plots with a grid, aligning them up and down by the same x-coordinate
grid.newpage()
grid.arrange(arrangeGrob(gA,gB,nrow=2,heights=c(.8,.3)))

# 
# output to file
pdf('prettyGSEApoint.pdf',width=8,height=4)
grid.arrange(arrangeGrob(gA,gB,nrow=2,heights=c(.8,.3)))
dev.off()

Figure 2: Line graph (enrichment score) + Barcode (rank)

Draw a line graph first

pline <- ggplot(result,aes(x=RANK.IN.GENE.LIST,y=RUNNING.ES,colour=pathway,group=pathway))+
  geom_line(size=1) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = mycol) + # draw dots with custom colors
  labs(x = "", y = "Enrichment Score", title = "") + 
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) + #xy0 let both the x and y axes start at 0
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0),
                     limits =c(min(result$RUNNING.ES-0.02), max(result$RUNNING.ES+0.02))) + 
  theme_bw() + # remove background color
  theme(panel.grid =element_blank()) + # remove gridlines
  theme(panel.border = element_blank()) + # remove outer border
  theme(axis.line = element_line(colour = "black")) +
  theme(axis.line.x = element_blank(),axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),axis.text.x = element_blank()) + #x remove x-axis
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) + #0x draw the x-axis at position 0
  theme(legend.position=c(0,0),legend.justification = c(0,0)) + #legend the legend is drawn in the lower left corner
  guides(colour=guide_legend(title = NULL)) + #colortitle hide the title of the legend generated by color
  theme(legend.background = element_blank()) +
  theme(legend.key = element_blank())

Figure 3: Barcode (enrichment score + rank) + Heatmap

enrichment score

list

Similar to a scatterplot, again the enrichment score of the genes in the pathway has to be extracted first.

Draw one at a time into the list

pbar <- lapply(unique(result$pathway), function(ii) {
    dd <- result[result$pathway == ii,]
    ggplot(dd,aes(x=RANK.IN.GENE.LIST,y=RUNNING.ES))+
      geom_bar(stat="identity",colour = "black")+
      labs(x = ii, y = "", title = ii) +
      theme_void() + # no coordinate system is drawn
      xlim(0, max(result$RANK.IN.GENE.LIST))
})
pbar

If a single pathway is drawn then this heatmap should be drawn to make sense. Drawing more than one would have to be this fake one, used only to indicate downward movement on the left and upward movement on the right.

t <- data.frame(a=as.numeric(1:1000),b=as.numeric(1:1000))

pheat <- ggplot(t,aes(a,1,fill=b)) +
  geom_tile()+
  theme_bw() + # remove background color
  labs(x = "Decreased--------------Increased", y = "", title = "") + 
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", mid = "white", high = "red",midpoint = 500)+
  scale_x_discrete(expand = c(0, 0)) + scale_y_discrete(expand = c(0, 0)) +#xy0 let both the x and y axes start at 0
  theme(panel.grid =element_blank()) + # remove gridlines
  theme(panel.border = element_blank()) + # remove outer border
  guides(fill=FALSE)#fill hide the legend generated by fill
pheat
